Taxus baccata

L
. (
Taxaceae
) is an evergreen conifer that belongs to the group of gymnosperms and grows best in mild oceanic climate with an annual rainfall of
>
1000 
L
/m 
2
(

). The European yew (

T. baccata

) and its numerous related cultivars, e.g., ‘Elegantissima’ and ‘Washingtonii’, ubiquitously occur in the Euro-Mediterranean region (

). Hybrids of 

Taxus
sp.

are found worldwide, such as 

T.
× 
media
Rehder

that originated from the hybridization of 

T. baccata

and 

T. cuspidata
Siebold & Zucc.

(

). 

Taxus
sp.

have gained scientific publicity because of their toxic needles and seeds, representing natural sources of the taxanes baccatin III and 10-deacetylbaccatin III that are precursors of the anticancer active paclitaxel (Appendino et al., 1993; Appendino, 1995; 

). Yew arils, i.e., the fleshy tissue that surrounds the naked seeds, have frequently been described as edible, fleshy, and energy-rich (

; 

). They are regularly consumed by humans either fresh or processed, e.g., in jams (

; 

). Although comparably low amounts of five taxane-derived compounds have been detected in arils for the first time, acute or chronic toxicity of yew arils cannot be concluded from the currently available data (

).

Fully ripe arils of 

Taxus
sp.

are attractive to birds owing to their mostly deep red color (

), which has been attributed to the 
retro
-carotenoid rhodoxanthin (Appendino, 1995; 

). In addition, β- carotene, zeaxanthin, eschscholtzxanthin, and eschscholtzxanthone have been tentatively assigned as minor carotenoids of red-fleshed 

T. baccata

arils (Bodea et al., 1964; 

), although their unambiguous identification has not yet been accomplished. Moreover, the pigment profiles of unfrequently occurring yellow to golden-orange arils have remained unclear (

; Appendino, 1995). The 
retro
-carotenoids eschscholtzxanthin, eschscholtzxanthone, and rhodoxanthin may be considered as compounds of particular interest due to their higher antioxidant capacity compared to that of β- carotene as reported by 

. Moreover, rhodoxanthin has been described to be a promising pigment for conveying bright red to purple color hues to foods and beverages using techno-functional formulations prepared thereof (

). The molecular structure of rhodoxanthin features an exceptionally large π- electron system of 14 conjugated double bonds, including two unusual exocyclic double bonds that have been reported to readily undergo (
E
)- to (
Z
)-isomerization upon dissolution in solvents and even mild thermal treatments (

). In nature, abundant amounts of (6 
Z
)- and (6 
Z
,6 
′
Z
)-rhodoxanthin were frequently encountered in rhodoxanthin-containing plant tissues, e.g., the leaves of 

Taxodium distichum

(
L
.) Rich. and 

Cryptomeria japonica

(Thunb. ex 
L
.f.) D.Don (

) or the red-colored berries of 

Lonicera
sp.

(

). However, a comprehensive profiling of genuine carotenoids, including geometrical isomers and esters, is not yet available for differently colored arils of cultivars of 

T. baccata

and related hybrids.

Representative HPLC-DAD chromatograms of carotenoids from red (a) and yellow (b) arils of
Taxus sp.
and cultivars according to Table 1 are illustrated in Fig. 1 . In total, 43 carotenoids were detected in our study ( Tables 2 and 3 ). Carotenoid profiles of both red- and yellow-colored arils were dominated by retro -structured xanthophylls, i.e., (all- E )-rhodoxanthin ( 19 ), (all- E )-eschscholtzxanthin ( 21 ), and various geometrical isomers derived thereof ( 5 , 6 , 8–17 , 20 ). Less abundant free carotenoids were identified as (all- E )-violaxanthin ( 1 ), (all- E )-lutein ( 2 ), (all- E )-zeaxanthin ( 3 ), and (all- E )-β- carotene ( 18 ). Moreover, esters of β- cryptoxanthin ( 22 , 23 , 26 ), lutein ( 24 , 25 , 27 , 28b , 30 ), eschscholtzxanthin ( 28a , 33 , 35 , 37–43 ), and eschscholtzxanthone ( 29 , 31 , 32 , 34 , 36 ) were assigned, having fatty acyl moieties of lauric, myristic, and palmitic acid. The genuine carotenoid profiles obtained from red- and yellow-fleshed arils unraveled a broader diversity of carotenoids within the species
T. baccata
and
T. × media
compared to that of previous studies reporting solely rhodoxanthin as the major carotenoid (Appendino, 1995;
). Eschscholtzxanthone, eschscholtzxanthin, β- carotene, and zeaxanthin have been reported as minor carotenoids of
T. baccata
arils (Bodea et al., 1964;
), although an unambiguous identification had not been achieved. We now present a detailed characterization of free and esterified carotenoids, being identified on the basis of comprehensive HPLC-DAD-ESI/APCI-MS
n
data ( Tables 2 and 3 ; Figs. 1–3 ) as described in the following.

Compound 2 was identified as (all- E )-lutein, showing molecular ions [M] +• at m/z 568 and, at low abundance, protonated molecules [M + H] + at m/z 569 in the ESI positive ion mode. An abundant in-source fragment at m/z 551 ([M + H – H 2 O] + ) was formed in the ESI(+)-MS 1 experiment, resulting from the spontaneous elimination of water at the ε- ring as reported earlier by
and Schex et al. (2018). The ESI(+)-MS 2 spectrum revealed a base peak at m/z 533 ([M + H – 2 H 2 O] + ). In accordance with the literature (Schex et al., 2018;
), the fragment ions detected at m/z 495 ([M + H – H 2 O – 56] + ) and m/z 429 ([M + H – H 2 O 122] + ) were attributed to retro -- Diels-Alder fragmentation of the ε- ring and cleavage of hydroxylated ε- or β- rings, respectively.

Compounds 12 , 16 , and 19 were the three major carotenoids in red-colored arils ( Fig. 1a ), being identified as (6 Z ,6 ′ Z )-, (6 Z )-, and (all- E )- rhodoxanthin, respectively. Furthermore, six minor compounds were assigned to rhodoxanthin isomers ( 5 , 6 , 8 , 9 , 11 , 14 ) in accordance with a thermally isomerized reference standard ( Table 2 ). All rhodoxanthin ( E/Z )-isomers displayed protonated molecules [M + H] + at m/z 563 using ESI positive ion mode. In the ESI(+)-MS 2 experiment, the aforementioned compounds showed base peaks at m/z 359, as representatively illustrated in Fig. 2a for (all- E )-rhodoxanthin ( 19 ). Abundant product ions were detected at m/z 545 ([M + H 18] + ) and m/z 507 ([M + H 56] + ), presumably resulting from the loss of water and retro - Diels Alder fragmentation, respectively. Moreover, ESI(+)-MS 2 spectra revealed fragment ions at m/z 479 ([M + H 84] + ) that may derive from retro -Diels Alder fragmentation (56 amu) and carbon monoxide elimination (28 amu). Further distinct product ions appeared at m/z 425, 389, 281, and 209. The abundant fragment ions at m/z 425 and 359 have been previously reported for rhodoxanthin (
). UV/vis spectra (see Table 2 and Fig. 3 ) displayed main absorption maxima ( λ max ) ranging from 478 to 502 nm across the rhodoxanthin ( E/Z )-isomers assessed, being detected at 502 nm for (all- E )-rhodoxanthin as well as at 494 and 486 nm for (6 Z )- and (6 Z ,6 ′ Z )-rhodoxanthin, respectively. Therefore, ( E )- to ( Z )-isomerization at the exocyclic double bonds of rhodoxanthin provoked hypsochromic shifts of 8 nm each compared to that of the (all- E )-configured molecule, being in accordance with previous reports in addition to the characteristic elution order of those rhodoxanthin ( E/Z )-isomers (
). Further absorption signals were detected at 316–336 nm across the rhodoxanthin ( E/Z )-isomers assessed, resulting in a narrow range of DB/DII ratios (15–23%). Thus, no characteristic absorption bands in the near UV region, i.e., so-called ( Z )-peaks (Britton, 1995), were obtained that would have supported the tentative assignment of ( Z )-configured double bond positions at the inner polyene chain. Previously, it has been suggested on the basis of molecular modelling and steric considerations that preferred positions for the ( E/Z )-isomerization at rhodoxanthin’ s inner polyene backbone might be the C-8,9 and C-12,13 double bonds (
).

In addition to the above-described free carotenoids, several xanthophyll esters were assigned in our yew arils on the basis of comprehensive HPLC-DAD-APCI-MS
n
data ( Table 3 ), comprising fatty acyl moieties of 200, 228, and 256 amu that correspond to lauric, myristic, and palmitic acid, respectively. For instance, three esters of β- cryptoxanthin ( 22 , 23 , 26 ) were identified by comparing their retention times, UV/vis spectra, and MS data to those of reference peaks obtained from an extract of papaya flesh (
Carica papaya
L .) and the respective literature (
). Compounds 22 , 23 , and 26 displayed protonated molecules [M + H] + at m/z 763 in the APCI (+)-MS 1 spectra. CID of the precursors ( m/z 763) yielded base peaks at m/z 535 ([M + H 228] + ) owing to the neutral loss of myristic acid. Further abundant product ions at m/z 671 ([M + H 92] + ), m/z 443 ([M + H – 228 92] + ), and m/z 413 ([M + H 228 122] + ) were in accordance with previous reports (
;
), resulting in the assignment of the aforementioned peaks to β- cryptoxanthin myristates. However, their geometrical isomers may not be distinguished using MS
n
fragmentation patterns. Therefore, we assigned the peaks 23 and 26 to the (all- E )- and (9 Z )-configured molecules of β- cryptoxanthin myristate, respectively, on the basis of the elution order and UV/vis spectral shape resembling those of an isomerized reference standard of free β- cryptoxanthin (data not shown).

