Light micrographs of fresh aril tissue of
T. baccata
‘Hessei’ and ‘Lutea’ both revealed cluster of small and round-shaped chromoplasts of red and yellow color, respectively (c.f. Fig. 4a and b ). The shapes of the chromoplasts of both red and yellow-colored yew arils were similar to those of mamey sapote pulp and goji berries (Chacon-Ord´o´nez ˜et al., 2016;
), whereas elongated, needle-shaped, crystalline carotenoid structures were not observed as typically found in tomatoes and carrots (
). However, chromoplasts of yellow arils from
T. baccata
‘Lutea’, predominantly containing ( E/Z )-isomers and esters of eschscholtzxanthin instead of oxo- retro -carotenoids like rhodoxanthin, appeared to be very luminescent using polarized light, while chromoplasts of red-fleshed arils did not show this phenomenon. These findings indicate that the respective carotenoids in yellow yew arils were deposited in the aril tissue in a highly ordered or even crystalline state. This highly ordered form might comprise H-type aggregates that have been reported earlier for other dihydroxy-carotenoids like lutein and zeaxanthin, but might also comprise J-type aggregates as have been reported for xanthophyll esters (
). By contrast, polarized light microscopy revealed that the carotenoids present in the chromoplasts of our red-colored arils, i.e., mostly containing ( E/Z )-isomers of rhodoxanthin and eschscholtzxanthone esters, were deposited presumably in a non-ordered or low-ordered state. In fundamental studies on the aggregation of rhodoxanthin, isomers with ( Z )-configured double bonds at the inner polyene backbone have been reported to hamper aggregation at abundances of > 3% (
). In our red-colored arils, those rhodoxanthin isomers ( 5 , 6 , 8 , 9 , 11 , 14 ) contributed to 6–15% of the total rhodoxanthin concentration and, therefore, their presence might explain the lacking luminescence of red chromoplasts under polarized light. However, further study is warranted because the currently available knowledge on deposition forms or aggregate types of retro --carotenoids like rhodoxanthin, eschscholtzxanthone, and eschscholtzxanthin is very scarce, in particular, in plant tissues.

